## Vercel Web Analytics Configuration

Successfully configured Vercel Web Analytics for the BunkMax Next.js project.

### Changes Made

#### Modified Files:
- **frontend/app/layout.tsx** - Added `<Analytics />` component to the root layout
  - The `@vercel/analytics` package was already installed (v2.0.1)
  - The Analytics import was already present
  - Added the `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag as per official Vercel documentation
  - Placed the component after the main content to ensure proper rendering order

- **frontend/package-lock.json** - Updated by npm install to ensure dependency integrity

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Analytics quickstart guide (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart):

1. **Framework Detection**: Identified this as a Next.js App Router project (app/layout.tsx exists)

2. **Package Installation**: The `@vercel/analytics` package (v2.0.1) was already present in package.json

3. **Integration**: Added the `<Analytics />` component to the root layout following Next.js App Router best practices:
   - Imported from `@vercel/analytics/next`
   - Placed within the `<body>` tag
   - Positioned after the main content providers

4. **Verification**: 
   - Build completed successfully with no errors
   - Linting passed with no new errors introduced
   - TypeScript compilation successful
   - All 12 routes generated correctly

### Next Steps for Deployment

To fully activate Vercel Web Analytics:
1. Enable Analytics in the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Deploy the changes using `vercel deploy`
3. Verify tracking by checking browser Network tab for `/_vercel/insights/*` requests
4. Monitor analytics data in the Vercel project dashboard

### Notes

- Analytics component is now properly configured and will start tracking when deployed to Vercel
- No additional configuration is required for basic page view and visitor tracking
- Custom events are available for Pro/Enterprise plans if needed in the future
